Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that lets OCaml code walk a libpcapng file and run an OCaml callback for every captured frame.

* The public OCaml interface lives in **`pcapng.mli`**.  
* The C/​C++ glue lives in **`pcapng_stubs.cpp`** (it must be compiled as C++).  
* A tiny `pcapng.ml` wrapper is also shown – it only exposes the abstract type
  and forwards the three primitives.

You can drop the three files in a directory, add the stanza shown at the end
to your `dune` project, and you will have a ready‑to‑use OCaml library called
`pcapng`.

---

## 1. OCaml interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(** libpcapng bindings – iterator style API *)

(** An opaque handle to an opened pcapng file. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.  All fields are copied out of the C++ object,
    therefore the OCaml value owns its own copy of the packet payload. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp    : float;      (** seconds since the Unix epoch (as in libpcap) *)
  captured_len : int;        (** number of bytes stored in the file *)
  original_len : int;        (** original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data         : bytes;      (** raw packet bytes, length = captured_len *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Failure] if the file cannot be
    opened or the format is invalid. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a previously opened file.  The handle is also automatically closed
    by the finaliser, so calling [close] is optional but useful for deterministic
    resource release. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Walk the whole file, calling the supplied OCaml function for each frame.
    The callback is executed **inside the OCaml runtime**, so it may allocate,
    raise exceptions, etc.  If the callback raises, iteration stops and the
    exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter_frames : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
```

