## 5. Example usage (OCaml)

```ocaml
(* test_pcapng.ml *)
let () =
  let p = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  Printf.printf "Iterating over frames …\n";
  Pcapng.iter_frames p (fun fr ->
      Printf.printf "ts=%f cap=%d orig=%d data_len=%d\n%!"
        fr.timestamp fr.captured_len fr.original_len (Bytes.length fr.data)
    );
  Pcapng.close p
```

Compile with `dune exec ./test_pcapng.exe` (or `ocamlc -I _build/default ...`).

---

### What the binding does, in a nutshell

| OCaml side | C++ side |
|------------|----------|
| `type t` is an OCaml custom block holding a `Reader*`. | `Reader` opens the file, owns an internal iterator. |
| `open_file` → allocate custom block → `new Reader(path)`. | |
| `close` → delete the `Reader*`. | |
| `iter_frames handle cb` → C++ loop `for (it = r->begin(); it != r->end(); ++it)` | |
| For each `Frame` we allocate an OCaml 4‑tuple (`float * int * int * bytes`). | |
| The tuple is passed to `caml_callback(cb, tuple)`. | |
| If the OCaml callback raises, the exception propagates out of the stub and iteration stops. | |
| The custom finaliser also deletes the `Reader*` if the user forgets to call `close`. | |

The design follows the usual “custom block + finaliser” pattern, ensures the
runtime is released while the pure C++ iterator runs (so the GC can work in
parallel), and safely reacquires it for each callback.  It is thread‑safe as
long as you only use the handle from a single OCaml thread (the same guarantee
as the rest of the OCaml runtime).  

You now have a clean, idiomatic OCaml API that lets users write:

```ocaml
Pcapng.iter_frames pcap (fun f -> …)
```

and have their own OCaml code executed for *every* frame that libpcapng yields.
